Visualizations

LA Airbnb Visualizations

This page shows several key visualizations from our analysis and highlights the enriched variables we created: price per person, amenity flags, annual revenue, stay type, and review score.

Code 
### Visualization: Price Distribution 
import plotly.express as px
# Filter price range for visualization
price_cap = 500
df_price_plot = df[df['price_num'].between(0, price_cap)]

fig_price_dist = px.histogram(
    df_price_plot,
    x='price_num',
    nbins=50,
    title='Distribution of Nightly Price (0–$500)',
    labels={'price_num': 'Nightly price (USD)'}
)
fig_price_dist.show()
  1. Nightly Price Distribution (0–$500) The distribution of nightly prices in Los Angeles is right-skewed, with most listings clustered between $80 and $250 per night. This indicates that while LA does have luxury, high-priced properties, they represent a small portion of the market. The majority of Airbnb listings fall into a moderate and affordable price range.

df_pp_plot = df[df['price_per_person'].between(0, price_pp_cap)]

  1. Price Per Person Distribution When adjusting for the number of guests accommodated, price-per-person becomes much more concentrated, typically between $20 and $80 per person. This suggests that many higher-priced listings actually offer good value when shared by multiple guests. The distribution also highlights affordability differences between solo
Code 
### Visualization: Room type vs price 
df_room_plot = df[df['price_num'].between(0, price_cap)]

fig_room_price = px.box(
    df_room_plot,
    x='room_type',
    y='price_num',
    title='Price by Room Type (0–$500)',
    labels={'room_type': 'Room type', 'price_num': 'Nightly price (USD)'}
)
fig_room_price.show()
  1. Box Plot — Price by Room Type Entire homes/apartments consistently have the highest price range, with a noticeably larger spread and more extreme high-end listings. Private rooms tend to be moderately priced with lower variability, while shared rooms remain the most budget-friendly and tightly clustered. This pattern reflects the premium placed on privacy and full-property access.
  1. Top 15 Most Expensive Neighborhoods (Bar Chart) The most expensive neighborhoods show dramatically higher average prices, reflecting areas with luxury properties or tourist-driven demand. These neighborhoods cluster around premium coastal or central LA zones. The significant price differences indicate how strongly location influences listing value.
Code 
import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

# Clean price column if not already done
df['price_num'] = pd.to_numeric(
    df['price'].str.replace(r'[\$,]', '', regex=True),
    errors='coerce'
)

# Filter rows with valid ratings + prices
df_reviews = df[
    df['review_scores_rating'].notna() &
    df['price_num'].notna()
].copy()

# ----- Choose fixed filter values -----
min_rating = 4.0     # minimum acceptable review score
max_price = 500      # maximum price to show
# --------------------------------------

# Apply the filters
filtered = df_reviews[
    (df_reviews['review_scores_rating'] >= min_rating) &
    (df_reviews['price_num'] <= max_price)
]

# Build title
title = f"Price vs Review Score (Rating ≥ {min_rating}, Price ≤ ${max_price})"

# Create scatter plot
fig = px.scatter(
    filtered,
    x="review_scores_rating",
    y="price_num",
    color="room_type",
    opacity=0.6,
    title=title,
    labels={
        "review_scores_rating": "Review Score Rating",
        "price_num": "Nightly Price (USD)",
        "room_type": "Room Type"
    }
)

fig.update_layout(height=500)
fig.show()

Price vs. Review Score (Static Visualization): This scatter plot explores whether higher guest review scores are associated with higher nightly prices.
Listings are filtered to include only properties with strong ratings (4.0 or above) and prices under $500 per night.
Each point represents an Airbnb listing, colored by room type.
The chart shows that while higher-rated listings span a wide range of prices, extremely low-rated listings tend to cluster at cheaper price points, suggesting that quality and guest satisfaction can influence pricing but are not the only determining factors.
